The EU announces that it made €2.2 billion available in 2010, leading to the right path to upholding its promise of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
These funds are "new and additional" under the Copenhagen Accord to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without the detriment of Public aid for development.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and an additional" means.
While the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
The European Commission, for example, considered 2009 to be a reference: international funding has been preserved, and it adds 150 million to it for the three-year fast start funding title.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment terms or terms at the level of public aid for development.
By contrast, France considers that the financing of 'all new projects' of 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or the global level of Public Aid for the Development of d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the total amount of support for France towards developing countries may remain constant (or even reduced), to honour its commitment to "new and additional funding...
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
There is no rule yet, and each chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as. France, considering that 1€ borrowed is equal to 1€ for the donated.
It is clearly hard to prove to be: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be supported for some of the investments that are profitable (often the projects associated with reducing emissions, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we receive as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , we should not understand it as part of our obligations, but as a loan price for the creditor country (i.e. the interest rate equivalent).
But France can only make such a justification: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros, of which 91.5% is the loan (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (€36.1 million) - see the EU document to be able to verify this for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses a loan on such a scale.
Germany has requested 46% of this place, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) abide by their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives €1 to its promise in satisfaction, France will only give 10 centims and consider this effort to be comparable.
Beautiful juggling piece!
To summarise, in its financing of the "fast start" France operates with a double cheat: on the one hand, the development of the share in time and, on the other, with a real financial burden.
Although it spends only €36.1 million, it can convince that it spends €420 million "new and additional" in connection with his promises.
The Finance Minister's handling (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would the Member States continue to donate if they just have to lend?) and in negotiations, because developing countries are not entirely naive...
The early financing chapter is just a small question mark, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be a grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case for us.
Whatever it is, it is essential to draw on the lessons of this first year of early funding.
France should first announce a change in its way of keeping the accounting records for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and decency and justice to other European Union countries.
But above all, France should avoid a debate on deposits in long-term funding (another major chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the issue of 'additionality' or how to book loans.
France should change its position to become as progressive for these deposits as in others.
Hope is therefore being put in the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciuko-Morizet, who will come to Cancun next week.
France's surprise fast-track announcement and its vision for "additional" and the use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international confidence, necessary to move forward in discussions.
An alarm about pesticides that children ingest.
The 10-year-old will be immortally ingested in one day by 81 different chemicals, according to one study published this Wednesday, by the Future Generations Association (ex-Men for Rights and Preservation of Future Generations).
The Association, which points out that its results "do not have a significant statistical value with regard to the low number of samples analysed but are characteristic of the processed issue," bought between July and September of foods commonly consumed in four meals and one light meal as a light snack per child of roughly 10 years in supermarkets in l'Oise and Paris.
These typical dishes, including official recommendations - five fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - as well as confectionery,they were analysed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other polluting agents.
The plate's balance is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are listed as carcinogenic, possible or likely, and five substances are among the clear carcinogenic substances, as well as 37 substances that could act as disruptive to internal excrement glands (PEs), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Centre for Cancer Research.
"Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical admitted individually are not exceeded, in our research we can well see that the reality in exposing consumers to contaminating substances, perhaps carcinogenic, and/or PE is striking," the association says.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk contain about ten résidu, with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven to be certain carcinogens, as is the case with about 20 residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, reported by the study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a banned fungicidal agent in France.
The same goes for the green beans of Kenya, included in lunch, where the studios have discovered traces of the powerful insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, minced meat steak, tuna in a can and even buns and chewing gum were riddled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the water from the tap, the analysis revealed the presence of nitrate and chloroform.
The salmon's steak for dinner was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues discovered, and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave did not avoid analysis.
The final risk to the consumer of this "cocktail of contaminants" is likely to be underestimated," the study suggests.
The Ecological Europe-Greens Society (EE-LV) proposed "creaking to the emergency" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase of civilizational diseases."
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) examined the residue's state of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereal.
